[2] South Africa - human, animal
Date: Wed 7 Mar 2018, 3:08 PM
Source: ENCA [summ., edited]
https://www.enca.com/south-africa/six-people-diagnosed-with-rabies-in-south-africa


The National Institute for Communicable Diseases (NICD) reports that 5 people have contracted rabies since December last year [2017].

Patients with the disease were recorded in Limpopo, Mpumalanga, KwaZulu Natal (2 cases) and the Eastern Cape. Another suspected case was reported in the Free State in December [2017]. The patient was exposed to a domestic cat before falling ill. In this case, laboratory confirmation was not possible due to the lack of appropriate specimens.

Rabies in humans can be prevented through post-exposure prophylaxis.

The 6 reported rabies cases involved exposure to rabid domestic dogs (3 cases) and domestic cats (3 cases). Other animals may also become infected with and transmit the virus to humans, but such reports are less common.

