[4] Israel - canine, human exposure
Date: Mon 19 Mar 2018
Source: Arutz Sheva 7 [edited]
http://israelnationalnews.com/News/Flash.aspx/413458


The Ministry of Health reports the discovery of rabies in a stray dog at the entrance to the Tel Dan nature reserve in the Upper Galilee.

The ministry requests that anyone who may have been in contact with the infected animal or a stray animal in the area or who has animals that may have come into contact, urgently reach the nearest health office or hospital emergency room to consider preventive treatment. The ministry warned hikers and other vacationers in the area to be alert.

--
communicated by:
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>

[According to a circular distributed by Israel's Veterinary Services on Tue 20 Mar 2018, the stray dog described above attacked, on Sun 18 Mar 2018, 3 visitors in the Tel Dan Nature reserve, bordering Lebanon (map at https://tinyurl.com/ycwzqs3x). The attacked people killed the animal and sent it to the national rabies laboratory at Beit-Dagan, where rabies was confirmed. They were referred to the public health authorities for post exposure treatment. During 2017, 3 rabid animals were identified within the same nature reserve, all jackals; the most recent case was reported in August 2017. Neighbouring Lebanon has recently reported a rabies case in a dog to the OIE; its earlier reported case was submitted in 1995. The actual circulation of the virus in that country is clearly reflected in Israel's rabies map of 2015 at http://www.moag.gov.il/vet/Yechidot/Machon/maabada_kalevet/airueim%20kalevet/kalevet_2015/PublishingImages/rabiesmap272016.jpg.

The current case is Israel's 38th case in animals since the start of 2018, and the 1st dog among them; the others were 31 jackals and 6 calves (in separate locations; see the 2018 rabies map at http://www.moag.gov.il/vet/Yechidot/Machon/maabada_kalevet/airueim%20kalevet/Documents/mapa_kalevet_19_03.jpg).

The major rabies event in Israel, involving mainly jackals in the northern valleys, started in October 2017 and does not seem to have been controlled yet, in spite of reports on enhanced distribution of vaccine baits for wildlife. For further details, please refer to previous postings.

It may be assumed that the number of post-exposure treatments in humans since the start of the current event is higher than in previous years, but official figures, since October 2017, are still not available. - Mod.AS]
